Project Proposal¶

Introduction¶

In this challenge, I want to research the possibility of classifying tumours found in patients diagnosed with breast cancer. Specifically, I want to find out whether a machine learning algorithm can accurately predict whether a tumour is malignant (cancerous) or benign(non-cancerous), using the properties of tumours from the Breast Cancer Dataset (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/yasserh/breast-cancer-dataset) from Kaggle.

For this, I will try to apply the knowledge that I have gained at the beginning of this semester and create a cohesive document in which I will demonstrate what I'm going to research, what steps I will be taking to perform the research, and what the results of the research will be.

Domain Understanding¶

What is cancer?¶

According to Stanford Medicine, the definition of a cancer is a follows1:

Cancer is an abnormal growth of cells. Cancer cells rapidly reproduce despite restriction of space, nutrients shared by other cells, or signals sent from the body to stop reproduction. Cancer cells are often shaped differently from healthy cells, they do not function properly, and they can spread to many areas of the body. Tumors, abnormal growth of tissue, are clusters of cells that are capable of growing and dividing uncontrollably; their growth is not regulated.

In 2020, 18.1 million people globally were diagnosed with cancer cases2.

Breast cancer¶

Breast cancer is the most common type of cancer diagnosed among women. According to statistics from the World Health Organisation, 2.3 million women were diagnosed globally with breast cancer, with 685.000 women dying due to complications caused by breast cancer in that same year3. This puts the the global average mortality rate of breast cancer in the ballpark of about 30%, and is listed by Cancer Research UK as the second most deadly form of cancer, with lung cancers being the deadliest4.

Types of tumours¶

Tumours are divided between benign and malignant. Benign tumours grow slowly and do not spread, and are therefore easier and less destructive to remove. Malignant tumours on the other hand grow rapidly and tend to spread, invading and destroying tissue either locally (locally invasive) or by sending cancer cells to other tissue in the body (metastatic).


Why is research into machine learning for predicting breast cancer classification needed?¶

In traditional methods for determining the type of tumour that causes cancer, a patient will have a biopsy taken by a doctor, which will then be analysed by medical professionals. A biopsy is a procedure where sample tissue is taken from the affected part of the body, and then analysed in a laboratory to determine whether the tumour is benign or malignant. A biopsy takes between 15 and 30 minutes, and the results of the biopsy are either ready as soon as 2 days, or it may take as long as 10 days6.

If it is possible to use machine learning to get a highly accurate prediction from a tumour scan on whether the tumour is benign of malignant, it can significantly shorten the time and effort needed to make a diagnosis, and could allow for malignant breast cancer to be detected much faster during annual breast cancer checkups, which increases the chances of survival for the patient diagnosed with breast cancer.

What will we do in order to train an algorithm to predict breast cancer classification?¶

  1. First, it is important that we understand the topic that we want to perform research on, and that we can find data on the topic at hand that is usable to use in machine learning. This data has to be complete, and in cases where it might not contain all the information that we need, we have to add the data from other sources as well.
  2. Then, we have to import the data and clean it where necessary, in order to make the algorithm be able to intepret the data correctly. Therefore it is necessary to understand the data by knowing what the values represent and how they are represented in the dataframe.
  3. Once we have cleaned the data, we can finally feed the values into the chose ML algorithm. We need to select the type of algorithm that is most suitable to make the classification prediction (the AI Project Methodology document recommends the usage of Nearest Neighbours) and make sure that the data is fitted correctly. In the course of making the predictions, we can try and adjust other variables to see whether we can get a consistently more accurate result.
  4. Finally, when we are satisfied (or not) with the results from our algorithm, we need to be able to demonstrate what we did to receive the results from the algorithm, and collect the necessary feedback to improve and reflect on the project, and make adjustments where necessary.

Interviewing for domain understanding¶

As the topic this project is deeply rooted in healthcare, in which I am not an expert at all, there has only been so much information which I was able to find or confirm which relates to my domain understanding. Therefore, I found it important to speak to somewho who was in fact much more knowledgeable than me about (breast) cancers.

As my parents are currently active in the healthcare sector and have connections to many medical specialists, I was able to arrange a short interview with Drs. Aaldering, who is an Oncologist at the Laurentius hospital in Roermond. It was my intention to have an interview face-to-face, however Drs. Aaldering was facing a very tight schedule due to employee shortages and could therefore not meet in person. Therefore I held a (short) interview over the phone in which I asked the following questions in a semi-rigid structure. As this was a phone call, I was unable to record my conversation and therefore had to write down the answers that she was giving and translate these to English afterwards.

  • How often does breast cancer occur in people compared to other forms of cancer?

    Generally speaking, breast cancer is the most common form in which cancer cells manifest in a patient's body, followed by other types of cancer such as lung cancer, colorectal cancer, and prostate cancer. It is overwhelmingly prevalent with women, while breast cancer in men is found in less than 1% of breast cancer cases.

  • How high is the average rate of survival with breast cancer compared to other forms of cancer?

    This depends a lot on the stage at which the cancer is discovered and the type of growth as well. Breast cancer tumours in the first and second stages are very localised and are therefore easier to treat and survive. In the third stage, the cancer cells will have spread more in the region surrounding the origin of the tumour and therefore chemotherapy and/or mastectomy will be required. At stage four, the tumour will have spread to other parts of the body and therefore make treatment very difficult. However, compared to other types of cancer, breast cancer boasts a high survival rate in the western world due to advanced screening and treatment techniques. Yet other forms of cancer, such as lung cancer, are very lethal in comparison.

  • What makes malignant tumours so dangerous compared to benign tumours?

    Benign tumours are quite compact in shape, are capsulated and therefore do not spread around them, and tend to be slow-growing. This makes them easier to remove surgically and decreases the need for destructive treatments such as mastectomy or chemotherapy. Malignant tumours are the opposite, being irregular and spread out, and tend to grow quite fast. This makes them more difficult to remove as not all parts may be able to be removed, causing the cancer to grow back.

  • How are the results of a breast cancer screening analysed by means of mammography?

    Mammograms are taken by a specialised machine which compresses the breast and takes high-resolution x-ray images, which are then analysed by specialists who look for abnormal masses between the breast tissue. In case the specialists suspect or can clearly see an abnormal mass, they will likely take additional pictures and may take a biopsy of the breast. This will then be sent to a lab and analysed by specialists there. While mammograms are very manual in nature and require the skilled eyes and thinking of a specialist, they boast an accuracy of between 80% and 85% in identifying women with breast cancer.

  • Do you think that predictions about the type of tumour by means of AI could help medical specialists?

    I think that artificial intelligence can definitely play a role in detecting breast cancer tumour types, and I have heard of several studies looking into harnessing its potential. However, I do think that artificial intelligence should not have a leading role in determining treatment for the patient based on its diagnosis. Artificial intelligence should be a tool which can be used by medical specialists to help them determine what sort of tumour they could be dealing with here, and possibly start early treatment if warranted. I believe that it would be very risky to put the health of patients at the whims of computers, and I think that a human should make the final decision in this matter.

Target variable¶

For this project, I want to train my program to be able to detect whether it is currently detecting a benign tumour or a malignant tumour, based on two or more variables. As I'm trying to determine the type of tumour, I would need to make use of a Classification algorithm.

Data Provisioning¶

Data Requirements¶

To be able to collect the right data, I have to make sure that I understand where I have to retrieve it from. There is no use in collecting data that does not come from a reliable source, as there is a chance that this data is not accurate (anymore).

Sources¶

As the domain of breast cancer is almost wholly related to the overarching domain of healthcare, it would be preferable to use data originating from hospitals or medical specialists who have collected data on tumours found in breast cancer. This limits the amount of sources which can be utilised quite substantially, but this is not surprising as the domain itself is also quite limited in scope.

Stakeholders¶

Performing research on this topic raises the question of whom would potentially benefit from the usage or storage of this data? We can think of several stakeholders who would have stakes in publishing this data publically:

  • Medical specialists: Medical specialists who have performed the research and collected the results benefit from publishing their these, as it enables the scientific and medical community to evaluate the findings themselves. It allows other people to repeat or build on these results and confirm the findings themselves.
  • Breast cancer patients: Breast cancer patients can potentially benefit from storing this data as it allows other researchers to analyse the data and potentially find ways to make the classification of breast cancer tumours easier and faster, resulting in higher chances of survival as the cancer can be treated more rapidly.

Data Elements¶

The data that will be used to carry out this research is the Breast Cancer Dataset retrieved from Kaggle. Kaggle is a subsidiary company of Google which allows users to find and publish datasets for use in data science7. When we dig deeper, we find that the data originates from diagnosed cases collected by Dr. William H. Wolberg for the University of Wisconsin Hospitals in 1992. The University of Wisconsin Hospitals is an academic hospital in Madison, Wisconsin, United States of America, which can be assumed to be a reliable source of data to be used for serious ML application.

The dataset consists of 32 columns and 569 columns. Columns 3 till 32 are divided between the mean of the data, the standard error of the data, and the worst value of the data. It is provided as a CSV file and contains the following important data:

  1. ID: The unique identification number of the diagnosed case.
  2. Diagnosis: The general diagnosis made by a medical professional, classified by 'M' (malignant) and 'B' (benign).
  3. Radius: The distances from centre to points on the perimeter.
  4. Texture: The standard deviation of greyscale values.
  5. Perimeter: The measurements of the tumour perimeter.
  6. Area: The area measurements of the tumour.
  7. Smoothness: The local variation in radius lengths.
  8. Compactness: The tumour's compactness measurements calculated by perimeter^2 / area - 1.0.
  9. Concavity: The severities of concave portions of the contour.
  10. Concave points: The number of concave portions of the contour.
  11. Symmetry: The degree of symmetry of the tumour.
  12. Fractal dimension: The result of "coastline approximation" - 1.

Preprocessing¶

Now that we have the data we need to be able to conduct our research, and have determined which variables we wish to use for, it is time to actually make the data usable for input into the machine learning algorithm. In order to achieve this, we will go through the processes of Feature Selection, Splitting train/test, and Scaling.

Feature Selection¶

As stated previously, it is important to select the features which we want to use to predict the type of tumour found breast cancer. The first thing to do would be to convert any object-type variables into numerical values, as algorithms can only work with numbers. The only column in the dataset with object-type variables is diagnosis.

When looking for suitable variables, we want to look for variables that have the least amount of overlap between classes. In other words, plots which are the farthest away from eachother vertically.

Several variables do not have overlapping interquartile ranges (the spread of values between 25% and 75% of all values), such as compactness_mean, concavity_mean, concave points_mean, perimeter_mean, and area_mean.

We can use these variables to train the model and see what sort of accuracy we will be seeing. If the accuracy is short of our target variable, we can try and tweak some of the variables to see what works best.

Splitting train/test¶

In order to make the algorithm predict the type of tumour in breast cancer, we need to show it what the characteristics of past observations per class are. This will become the test set. Based on these characteristics, it will predict what the class for each observation in the train set is, and compare these with the actual class of each observation.

In [92]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.21, random_state=42)
print("There are in total", len(X), "observations.")
print("The train set now has", len(X_train), "observations.")
print("The test set now has", len(X_test), "observations.")

There are in total 569 observations.
The train set now has 449 observations.
The test set now has 120 observations.

In order to have a reproducible result for every time the code runs again, I went ahead and chose seed 42 for a consistent test/train set.

With seed 42, a test size of 21% gave me the most accurate predictions (94,16% accuracy) that came closest to my target variable of 95%.

Scaling¶

For this research, we are using the K-Nearest Neighbour algorithm to predict the class per observation, based on the given variables. In KNN, the prediction is made by estimating the likelyhood that a data point belongs to one class or the other based on the class of the nearest datapoints.8

The distance to the nearest datapoints is calculated using Euclidian distance, which is the absolute distance between two values. In order to ensure that the same unit of measurement is used among features, and that no features weigh more than others, we want to transform the values into the same unit of measurement, which will be Standard Deviation (SD) for this project.

Below, we use a scaler called StandardScaler in order to transform the values, after which we can visualise the results in a scatterplot.

In [93]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(X_train)
X_train = scaler.transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

sns.set(rc={"figure.figsize":(10, 6)})

ax.set(xlabel=X.columns[0], ylabel=X.columns[1], title="Distance between diagnoses (σ)")

Modelling¶

In the first step, we will actually load the K-Nearest Neighbours classifier algorithm and load in our dataset with the selected variables.

The second step will show us the accuracy of the predictions that the model made using our test/train set, by comparing the results of the predictions with the actual results in the individual observations.

In [94]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
model = KNeighborsClassifier()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
pred = model.predict(X_test)

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
acc = accuracy_score(pred, y_test)
print("Accuracy:", acc)

Accuracy: 0.9416666666666667

As I said earlier, with our current variables and test/train parameters, the model gives us an accuracy of 94,16%, coming very close to our desired target variable of 95%.

Evaluation¶

Now, we can evaluate the results from our model regarding accuracy. We will split the results by class so get an insight into whether the accuracy differs per class.

In [46]:
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
report = classification_report(y_test, pred, target_names=df_mean["diagnosis"].unique())
print(report)

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           M       0.94      0.96      0.95        71
           B       0.93      0.91      0.92        43

    accuracy                           0.94       114
   macro avg       0.94      0.93      0.93       114
weighted avg       0.94      0.94      0.94       114

We can see that there are small differences between the results of both classes.

Looking at the precision of predictions, out of the total amount of tumours predicted per class, 94% actually identified as Malignant tumours, while 93% actually identified as Benign tumours.

Looking further at the recall values, we can see that of these predictions, 96% of the Malignant tumours were correctly predicted, while 91% of Benign tumours were correctly predicted.

Lastly, the F1-score tells us how suitable the models are for predicting the tumour classes. The closer these values are to 1, the better the model fits. For Malignant tumours this is a score of 0.95, and for Benign tumours 0.92.

One reason for the difference in results between these classes could be visualised using the scaler.

In [96]:

Many of the observations for Benign tumours (2) are heavily concentrated around one point on the plot, while the observation for Malignant tumours (1) are more spread out. This could cause the outliers for Benign tumours to be mis-identified as Malignant tumours, as they are much farther away from the concentrated datapoints.

4. Conclusion¶

As seen in the modelling and evaluation above, the average accuracy of our model in predicting the type of tumour is 94,16%. While this falls just short of the target variable of 95% accuracy which I set for this project, it is still quite close to the mark and I think that it would be a viable way of determining tumour types with a high degree of accuracy.

It is also worth noting that the accuracy for malignant tumours is slightly higher than benign ones, which in my opinion is quite positive as malignant tumours are far more dangerous and require early treatment in order to increase the rate of survival.

Feedback¶

  • Drs Aaldering was very glad to meet with me again to discuss the progress that my research had made in the time between the interview and the demonstration. We had a small chat about how "official" this research was, and whether she would have to pay attention to anything in particular. I told her that I would particularly like her to comment on what would make the research clearer for her to understand.
  • I went through each chapter of the notebook with her, and talked her through the steps of how I came by the results of my research. I noticed that it was fairly straightforward for her to understand the project proposal and the data requirements, however she seemed to have some difficulty in understanding some of the graphs shown in data understanding, and later also the part of modelling the data. Personally, I feel that I went over these parts a little too quickly because I felt like I was actually taking too long (as Drs Aaldering still had a busy schedule, and I didn't want to take up too much of her time), and therefore I wasn't completely satisfied with how I tried to convey the technical part of my project.
  • When we arrived at the results of the research, she was quite impressed with the high degree of accuracy of my model. She reiterated from the domain understanding interview that the number for current methods of determining breast cancer types lies around 80 - 85% accuracy, and therefore thinks that the increase in accuracy definitely would help with starting up the appropriate treatments sooner.
  • She also reiterated from the previous interview that an algorithm with such a high degree of accuracy could be a very helpful tool for medical professionals to speed up cancer type diagnoses, but should never be the sole deciding factor in recommending treatment. She argued that medical professionals should always have the final decision in the kind of treatment, as they as human beings can rationalise with the patient and also recommend alternative ways of treating the cancer which might be more suitable.
  • After walking her through the research, she made several remarks regarding improvements. First, she felt that I could perhaps increase the accuracy of my model by using more data to train the model with. Second, she would have liked the layout to be a little more clear, as she found it hard to follow the text combined with the lines of code, and perhaps I could have supported my descriptions with more images. Finally, she said that she would have liked a more detailed explanation of the EDA and later modelling of the data.

Impact Assessment¶

In order to analyse what sort of an impact the trained model would have on the domain that it is related to, it is important to assess the capabilities and shortcomings of the model. This way, I can try to minimise the possible misuse of the model, either purposely or by accident. Especially since this model could be employed in a sector where human lives are on the line, I feel that it is important to chart who could benefit from the model, and how potent the model is.

I performed this assessment in cooperation with Drs Aaldering.

Impact on Society¶

  • What is exactly the problem? Is it really a problem? Are you sure?

    The problem is that with current technologies, the accuracy of determining the type of breast cancer is at around 85%. While this is a high percentage already, we feel that there is always room for improvement, as an improvement in accuracy means that more people can be treated for breast cancer sooner.

  • Are you sure that this technology is solving the RIGHT problem?

    We feel that this technology does not necessarily solve the problem, but it can be used as a tool by medical professionals to solve the problem of determining the type of breast cancer.

  • How is this technology going to solve the problem?

    This technology will help medical professionals solve the problem by making an accurate prediction of the type of breast cancer tumour and enabling treatment for people with breast cancer to start earlier.

  • What negative effects do you expect from this technology?

    We don't think that there will be many negative effects from this technology, as it would be mainly used as a tool to support medical professionals. There is a possibility that the accuracy might decrease if the data is used in real-time and collects more outlying observations, but other than that we don't think that the technology will have negative effects as it is only used in a controlled environment.

  • In what way is this technology contributing to a world you want to live in?

    The technology will enable medical professionals to make more accurate assumptions about cancer diagnoses, enabling breast cancer patients to receive the correct kind of treatment earlier. Late or incorrect treatment of breast cancer can result in insufficient or drastic treatment, which can be detrimental to the patients' health and wellbeing. I hope that this technology can help bridge the gap of the remaining 15% of inaccurate diagnoses using current diagnosing techniques, hopefully resulting in more lives being saved.

Privacy¶

  • Does the technology register personal data? If yes, what personal data?

    The technology does not register any personal data. The only data that is registered are the measurements taken from the breast cancer tumours, which are anonymous and not linked to any names or identifying markers.

  • Do you think the technology invades the privacy of the stakeholders? If yes, in what way?

    No, we don't think that this technology invades the privacy of stakeholders, as is does not record or register any information which can be used to infer their identity or disciminate against them.

  • Is the technology is compliant with prevailing privacy and data protection law? Can you indicate why?

    We are not aware whether the technology is compliant with any data protection laws, however as the technology does not register any personal data, we believe that there will we little in the way of breaching data protection laws.

  • In which way can you imagine a future impact of the collection of personal data?

    We do not believe that the technology contains any data which will affect the stakeholders in any long-term ways.

Human values¶

  • How is the identity of the (intended) users affected by the technology?

    The technology will be used as a tool by medical professionals to make a more accurate assumption about the type of breast cancer found in the tumour measurements from a patients. For a patient, this means that appropriate treatment can start sooner, increasing their survival rate and possibly mitigating insufficient or drastic treatment which could cause lasting damage.

  • How does the technology influence the users' autonomy?

    The technology will only be a tool for medical professionals to help determine the type of breast cancer in patients diagnosed with breast cancer. It will not have the final say about the appropriate treatment, which is still relegated to the medical professional. The patient is free to refuse or accept the suggested treatment or alternatives.

  • What is the effect of the technology on the health and/or well-being of users?

    We hope that the technology can be used to more accurately predict the type of breast cancer found in patients based on measurements of the tumour, therefore starting treatment earlier and increasing the rate of survival for the patient.
